result.execSummary:
The defendant Timothea L Stinnett was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Case called at 10:49am [ma]
Defendant Timothea L Stinnett in court with Attorney Paul A. Ksicinski.  Monica J. Hall appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Atty. Ksicinski verifies receipt of Amended Information; waives reading
--arguments given by ADA Hall in support of Amended Information
--the Court grants the State leave to file the Amended Information

Maximum penalties recited; Constitutional rights reviewed; plea of " NO CONTEST " entered to Count #1 of the Amended Information ; factual basis stipulated; victim rights compliance verified; the Court accepts the plea, finds Defendant guilty, and orders Judgment of Conviction entered.

On Motion of the State, the Court reads-in and dismisses Counts #2 and #3 of the Amended Information 

Sentencing arguments given by Counsel
The Court questions Ms. Stinnett

On Count #1, the Court withholds sentence, and places Defendant on Probation for 12 months, with conditions:

--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with recommended treatment per Agent
--to undergo assessment, treatment, or counseling as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--random drug and/or alcohol screening
--to obtain/maintain employment and/or education program as approved by the Agent
--no possession of controlled substance without valid prescription
--no contact with Corrine Quest or any other known drug offender except for treatment purposes as deemed appropriate per Agent
--to pay drug testing fee in the amount of $75
--to pay buy money reimbursement in the amount of $370
--to pay statutory costs

The Court determines that Defendant has already submitted a DNA sample
